Parliament has not ratified the amendment to the liberation of Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft to cancel the paragraph relating to the accusation of opposition leader Julia Tymosenko.
Deputies rejected in second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for having concluded a priori disadvantage agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not definitive and the court has to decide on the appeal of the convicted in December.
Tymoshenko calls the judgment a political revenge of the regime and has caused a process of suspicion of court partiality also in the west.
The draft to cancel paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It took 226 votes to approve it.
