Nutrition of an obese child: don’t take breakfast and take snack for dinner
More than one-third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of school students have a weight above the average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the patterns around it are.
On the tables of obese children, for example, cranberries are found 50% more frequently than in families of normal-weight children.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with a awareness action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In small-sized families sports is also not a habit, which is now the case of most schoolchildren today - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and participated 900 students from Czech primary schools.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", action supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have signed up to this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned indicate, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch - taste- dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet," said one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and snack at dinner
Experts draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone takes breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the questioned children do sports regularly but for parents this is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food
Another part of the survey allowed chosen children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food from options offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
“The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the ideal, in terms of a healthy diet.”
Among their favorite dishes there are a lot of cakes, meat and sweets.
“The most alarming thing is, in particular, a great preference for sweet lemonades,” it is said in the results of the survey.
For lunch, the pasta took the first place right before the white meat.
The children did not want fertilizers at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Head to Health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
“In the course of a review of a group of survey participants who had filled the questionnaire after the awareness session ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’, we witnessed a well-defined willingness to go towards a healthy diet,” the survey results indicate.
The most notable was for example when it comes to sweet lemonades because children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often choked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce the sweet dishes and the "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour or potato butter).
