How have travel prices changed since 1989
Until 1989, there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially in the countries of the socialist block, because the travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for vacation in Eastern Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel in Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination to the west and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist block (as well for the Czechs) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the West however it was necessary to make the hole all night with a bed bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for currencies which was the condition for traveling to the west was rejected to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czech currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain funds without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many countryside houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The Czech travel has experienced a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in Eastern Germany and Bulgaria were the maximum,the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are unconscious today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in neighboring western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits mainly in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechs could not travel by air to the west for a long time that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a Czech trip was at that time to bring with yourself its own conserve food, salmon, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the exchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our living level as well as average wage have increased which caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to the growing demand for travel travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with charter airlines that thanks to contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs had non-visum connections with almost most developed countries around the world except the EU that later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the post-revolution tourism history, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic was prepared.
Since this year as each year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the remote hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU removed the Czech tourist visas and allowed our country to be fully included in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including the attached charges.
