Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy – the way marketers have done it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members are fans of extreme-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes towards violence and their optimism about their own future.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and colleagues were able to interrogate 10,000 supporters from 14 extreme-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
“This is a new way to do research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, youth and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just an example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Reflective groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all subjects that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "I like", wall publications and statutory updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, the "data supernova" generates a search explosion, increasing the number of searches whose site name appears in the title by 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you could not approach in the street.
"Before, when you tried to conduct investigations on the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter," says Jamie Bartlett.
“Facebook avoids all of this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and deal with health and social problems.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunk performance were much more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
“You can’t deal with a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not be in another case unrecognized."
Facebook also continuously accesses the information of its users.
The data-care site team has studied statistics regarding the love situation and Valentine's Day, the rate of participation in the 2010 mid-mandate elections and a national happiness index (through the information only available - the digital freedom champions have long claimed that the site could make its treasure available to other people for search purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange to be able to play Scrabble with a friend that is thousands of kilometers away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey that they have not even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined instructions on how to collect information differently than by passing through the Internet, there is anything else about it online.
"I don't think that a large number of users have already thought that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were seen only by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things,” says Neil Selwyn.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technological researcher, Neil Selwyn thinks a notebook and a pen are the best tools that can be used.
