For someone known to hate deep interviews, Steve Jobs seems here surprisingly enthusiastic to expose technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to bring a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism rises, where he seems unattended to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him a bite to make him accelerate and move to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and tells his own vision of the future of computer science.
It’s a thing to read the posthumous ratings of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer in the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then puts them into practice.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
About how he learned to manage a company:
“For all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers are constantly the same, ‘oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
