“We were young and through this Blue Box we learned that we could create ourselves something capable of controlling billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn’t know much of both, but we knew how to invent a small thing capable of controlling great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have existed one day without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful tour he and Wozniak developed: he called to the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night by making himself to Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are called in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two complices go crazy laughing just before the Pope himself is awake.
About his love for technology (and the start of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett’s number in the directory and sends him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. C" was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP employees visiting the company’s research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first ever designed desktop computer.”
He was as big as a bag, possessed a small cathodic tube. I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was returned to HP and began writing programs for this machine.
Improvisation of Innovation:
In several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a headline.
At the beginning of his career, as he settles to sell a few printed circuit cards, a customer asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 credit days, he should take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties he encountered in developing a computer mouse:
