Eighty days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and which proved incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that sweep:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would be wrong and lose control over their market share.
“Let’s admit that you’re working with IBM or Xerox, you’re making a better copy or a better printer, and then?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [this are these types of people] who end up leading and product-specialized staff are put away from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely ruined by people who can’t imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product – the required manual work.
That’s what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s.
They pulled the defeat to victory.
Innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge portion of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtles.
There are compromises to do... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by bringing them together.
It is about trying to expose you to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved themselves the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
