How to detect a lie
A look at recent titles indicates how much deception and lies are omnipresent in everyday life.
Republican president candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been accused of scam for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach has sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open microphone telling U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lies destroyed carriers and convulsed countries.
The New York Congress member and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has passed for an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrevocable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violating the financing of campaigns related to covering an extra-marriage bond.
And then, no one who has lived the story will never forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave the test answers to students in order to make themselves clear about their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How much deception do we face?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are wicked lies.
Another study has shown that strangers lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detection or detection of lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, let’s say, charades, where the goal is to cry: “I’ve got you,” the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted a deep research of such projects, in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been disguised.
The liars look at you in the eyes.
They don’t bear, red, or don’t always irritate.
Not to conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A qualified lies detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, the formation of the question and the time of response.
I have spent several years examining scientific outcomes in the vast body and always emerging knowledge of fraud, and it is clear that detection of fraud is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include employment, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are skilled in reading others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know, according to research, that extraverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty to lie to you.
How can you say if someone lies?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what we call “setting data markers”.
This helps to provide a reference point to measure subsequent changes.
Watch the posture of your subject, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves his feet constantly so that they don’t launch unjust accusations when you see him moves his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for indications of verbal and non-verbal misleading behavior.
Consider these indications as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, look to a outlet, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated breath of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Questioners often wrongly indicate that the interview is finished just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Be careful with the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson has scratched using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Cheating individuals can also use a distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman...Mrs. Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of “wood language” when answering a difficult question: “Well... to say the truth... if I remember goods... to my knowledge.”
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize fraud is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid victimization by scammers in their professional and personal life.
