2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing billions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
The Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development reports that 582 million 835 hectares have been damaged, of which 78,03 per cent have suffered total damage and the remaining 21,07 per cent have suffered partial damage, the main plants damaged were vegetables, corn and corn.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year has been observed an accelerated increase, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 signals were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand signals unemployed, an increase by the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly depending on the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we observe is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity on the market due to a resource restriction by the legislation approved in Congress to fight money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy that they work to earn them, that they invest them and use them in something,” he says.
Prisoned migration
López Cervantes that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties in entry and second because when entering they already have a lot of difficulties in finding a job, these people stay here and ask for sources of work there, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the signal labour market is worsening considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails among the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the occupied population in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for deviation for the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of the Synaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of IED
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 the strongest decline in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State IED reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat of Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the third-party sector.
The debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July to the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the objective of reactivating the economy, the approval of the state congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November there was no profit from debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employer sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of governance capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
