The court validates "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital is one of the biggest changes that the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) debooted the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the House of Deputies formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogic cutting" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree that detailed the actions to follow to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was depleted because it did not reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, due to the fact that the regulation in the field of radio and television is a law-reserved attribution to the Federal Commission of Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
For the project only voted Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by accepting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions it planned for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the ministers decided to start the complaint formulated by the House of Deputies, without discussing the project for which the minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also consider that if he did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he reminded that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has for constitutional mandate the leadership of the state.
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years and this results in a better exploitation of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more chains.
Delaying the change, he said, would be delaying the benefits of digitalization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
“These questions require the operation of a whole system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, comprises a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State.”
He reminded that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they did it through the Executive, despite the fact that they had the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has in a form invaded the sphere of competences of the Congress, as it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislative, he assures.
