The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality as regards the election process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Programme of preliminary election results (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total protocols.
In this sense, the Chairman of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, reminded that a few days ago, last 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards to the federal electoral reform.
It will be remembered that Michoacán has not approved neither his Political Constitution nor his Electoral Code of the State or his Electoral Justice Act, while the State Congress has approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for this electoral trial to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has omitted its publication within the deadlines provided for by the Law of the Official Journal of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same 9th November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called "invalid and illegal" the voting of the state mandate for constitutional reforms, because it has no right to "sanction or contest them."
Interviewed on the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the IEM General Council it will be possible to make the partial and total countings of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no voting protocol and the count in the dosage of the urne is not at the president of it; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the protocols.
Furthermore, the total count of votes received in all elections may be made when there is an indication of the fact that the difference between the supposed candidate winning the respective election and the one who won the second place in the election is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition of the representative of the party and/or coalition who presented the second of the candidates.
The total calculation of the vote can also be made if at the end of the common calculation it results that the difference between the supposed winning candidate and the second place is equal or less than a percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party whose candidate came out second, the case in which the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial calculation are excluded.
It must be mentioned that this is the situation of Morelia’s election, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total protocols.
