The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy at the edge of the economic disaster and threatened the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, named on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he presents a cabinet composed in his majority of technocrates, although it is not clear when the new executive will take over his position.
Monti said he was going to present the president the result of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to overcome this difficult phase,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
“The framework is now well drawn,” he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that pushed its debt costs to levels impossible to support.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti has to approve a hard austerity package required by European leaders to recover confidence in Italy that had been affected.
By emphasizing the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability placed the yield of Italian BTP bonds to 10 years above 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of the Italian patronal Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts will have a good outcome,” said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the Technocrate majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and patronal groups and youth and women’s organizations on Monday.
He will finish his tour of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named on Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a short rest at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt now have returned to critical levels among the uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of €1.9 billion, would be too much for the current financial defences of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the generalized predictions that politicians will only give him the time to apply the reforms before the elections advance.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist on the fact that this should only be trained by specialists, an indicator of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
