Cruz López that this investigation is the result of health professionals’ concern for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic increase,” the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
He that in average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American inheritance, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that generally, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess of energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
