Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales - meat pasta with corn flour embedded in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
The UNAM asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signals that the paved were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis every rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous paved is appropriate, the cassis could be reduced or even completely eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for develops modified asphalt with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and consequently, the formation of cassis.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltens, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltens, which together give the paved its characteristic visco-elastique behavior.
The asphalt's visco-elastique behavior consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has a solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, he added.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible paved, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more surface layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he indicates, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, this allows the forces to spread very well in the paved.
If we had a modified asphalt, they would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer called rolling layer is placed, made of fine stone, i.e., of sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adherence in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is moist, the water is spread inside the layer it is difficult to get it out, which crushes all layers of the paved and consequently causes cassis.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he says, the first that is broken is the rolling film and only later the asphalt layer is affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paved must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on the asphalt, for example, bitumine emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow repairs to be easily and without having to use high temperatures.
