Some displaced protesters brought and distributed at that time copies of this judicial order and they even delivered it to the agents who watched the place, which caused 'some small confrontations', Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials hit the protesters.
The judicial order prohibits authorities to evacuate members of Occupe Wall Street or to "apply laws published after the beginning of the occupation or to prohibit protesters from reaching the park with tents or other properties they used before."
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, due to this judicial order, the city had suspended the re-opening of space to the public and protesters, whom he, however, warned of the fact that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The municipal counsel personally defended the evacuation carried out in the morning at the Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because of the fact that the protesters 'violated the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people came not to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to hurt others" because "some stores had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
“The evacuation of this morning in the morning has been disgusting and demonstrates that in the background Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of U.S. workers,” the spokesman added, who accused the mayor of “not respecting freedom of expression.”
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they do not think to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
