Japan regains after earthquake
GDP rises by 1.5 percent thanks to domestic consumption and ends the drop spiral in early March
Since March the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, recovering even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster of the country since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government calculated the material losses to $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, GDP data between July and September served to permanently turn the page: GDP increased 1.5 percent compared to the previous quarter and 6 percent in annual rate.
The recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partially explained by the recovery of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline of capital spending observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulant of the Japanese economy is not exclusively based on the Keynesian impulse that calls for to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate – or reconstruct – infrastructure, using the deficits to grow from zero.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan’s GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by the increase in costs on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen – the Nippon currency – became one of the “aside values” chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the eurozone and the U.S. forecast disturbances, a privilege that weighs as a layer in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious reverse for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, made responsibility for their low results between July and September the share of the yen.
While the markets continue their seats in the peripheral countries of the EU, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower the guard.
“We need to follow the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of certain foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid assessment of the yen,” said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa.
The prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that predicts the inflation points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are blocked.
For this declined four decimals to 100,4 points, compared to 100,8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is at the level 100, n falling eight decimal to 99.13 points.
