It is necessary to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, and that beyond cases of cancer.
The Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and take measures for this purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts related to various fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends the government to amend the Criminal Code in such a way that assisted suicide and euthanasia may be allowed, where such a choice is necessary, with a patient judged competent to make such a decision.
The experts quote a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
If Canada is ranked 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death.”
Medication or not, 77% of Canadians have no access to palliative care, reports experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire that most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
In the country, it is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the delicate question of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said not to want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
But, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on uncompetent or unconsented persons.
On the contrary, the report’s co-signator, Jocelyn Downie, said in a teleconference, there would be more cases of these overwhelms in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
“Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal.”
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already expressed their favour to euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of life to relieve their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
