Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized in various angles – the engraving of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the number, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of “land of human rights” of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Libération du 23 mai) proclaiming in the passage that France "not needs foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't welcome all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared to both left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference depends on the degree of generosity that will be granted to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande cants to banalities, indicating that co-development will allow us to solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is electorally paid; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron remind in a recent book that summarizes the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restriction of immigration is anemic to growth and harm employment.
The fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are at risk of replacing themselves with national workers, especially the unqualified, exercising a lower pressure on their wages.
But the experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitute to national employees, exercising for the most of the professions in sectors in shortage of employment.
Low-qualified immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the job offer.
Positive Effects on Wages
Just as a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country that has a shortage of anesthesiists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri thus calculated that an increase of 1% of migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% of real long-term wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a strong proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, at an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (low expenditure revenue) of €150,000 to the public budgets in average for his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to go to search for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The tooth in question, serving to dissuade immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
