North Stream, the new gateway of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It has to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brightness.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on Tuesday, on the borders of the Baltic, between orchestra and final buffet, in the inauguration of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his homologue from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe through a first tube of 1.224 km connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second tube will be completed by the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely and timely completion of this enormous building has airs of victory.
The project was strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will enable the supply of gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Thus, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to the Western European markets.
In the strongest of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
The subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by bringing its support to this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of Europe’s energy, since the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, strongly gas consumers, and whose deposits are in decline.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically,” Fillon confirmed by inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical outcome.
The submarine tube is made of steel gained from concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mining fields dating from World War II.
“A hundred people had to be kidnapped or destroyed, for caution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also an increase in measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, heavily as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but the project managers renounced it as the Swedish were unwanted to see a Russian state company establishment permanently outside their coasts.
“In the event of a disaster, we stop the passing of the gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned welding to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The surveillance of the state of the gas pipeline is provided by a submarine robot, traced by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
From the shape of a cigarette, it is introduced inside the tube, width of a meter of diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
At arrival, after three full days of journey at a speed of 3 meters a second, he provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply secured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of its shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15,5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint company, named Nord Stream, responsible for building and operating the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is favorable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for twenty renewable years, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
The funding for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided at 30% by shareholders and at 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the construction is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back in their expenses, as Gazprom alone takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted by pins.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas output door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that comes, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
With full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine is a brand book.
Founded about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a smell of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine book, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the skin mole (the taup skin) that indicates a painted cotton used to cover bankets for example.
This type of book was very appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine gave the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million passed coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It’s hard to set up a buyer’s portrait-robot, because the notebook attracts both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
In the image of Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, has 100 today and has since 2008 two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in the bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre and has been able to impose her identity.
“We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition " Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own booklet.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Getting advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agenda, stylos, computer houses... The brand declines on a wide range of supports.
A success that made jealous: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of people with disabilities so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for Disabled Employment begins today.
Despite a volunteer public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled persons is still twice higher than the average: 19%, against 9% for the entire population.
to disguise?
“No,” says Eric Blanchet, Director-General of the Adapt, the association that organizes the Week for Disabled Employment.
“The progress achieved over the past 15 years is considerable.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
“There is still a lot to do.”
It should be said that for disabled unemployed, obstacles remain many before accessing employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% in average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree and on the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled people, against 38% in average.
In short, so many criteria that particularly complicate the return to employment, and that “represent the node of the problem,” according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help recruit disabled workers.
This is for the objective brakes.
It remains the unknown, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise for the City association indicated that the managers surveyed had “a low level of knowledge of disability,” with a “overrepresentation of people on a wheelchair, mental or intellectual disabled.”
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, which date from 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of the Afegiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of “taxed” establishments, as well as the amount paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on, explains Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also translates a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of the establishments of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies of 100 to 199 employees.
